# Next.js and SSE standards

## Purpose
Guide implementation for a Next.js App Router frontend with real-time progress updates.

## Next.js defaults
- Use App Router conventions.
- Prefer Server Components by default.
- Use Client Components only when local state, effects, browser APIs, animation libraries, or event streams require them.
- Keep server/client boundaries explicit.

## SSE guidance
- Use SSE for one-way real-time progress and status updates from backend to frontend when appropriate.
- Place streaming route handlers in App Router API routes using the correct response headers for event streams.
- Ensure cleanup on disconnect or abort.
- Design stream payloads as typed events with explicit names and minimal payloads.
- Keep the client subscription logic in a dedicated hook.

## Data flow
- The page shell should subscribe to the stream, dispatch reducer actions, and pass derived state into phase components.
- Avoid duplicating stream parsing logic across components.
- Prefer one source of truth for current phase, slot status, progress, and final artifacts.

## Implementation preferences
- Use Tailwind for styling.
- Use Framer Motion for state-driven transitions in Client Components.
- Keep shared helpers in lib and stream logic in hooks.
- Prefer small reusable components over page-local duplication.

## Error handling
- Handle stream failure, timeout, and unexpected payloads visibly in the UI.
- Provide fallback UI for missing data and incomplete phases.
- Never leave the interface in an ambiguous "thinking forever" state.

## Performance
- Minimize unnecessary client-only rendering.
- Avoid expensive continuous effects across the whole page unless they are lightweight and justified.
- Mount heavy animated effects only when visible and useful.

## Do
- Keep App Router structure clean.
- Create dedicated hooks for SSE and reducer wiring.
- Make server/client responsibilities obvious in code.

## Do not
- Do not turn the whole app into a Client Component without need.
- Do not scatter EventSource setup in multiple files.
- Do not couple API route details tightly to leaf UI components.
